eb?topicID=1814.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: win !</span><hr size=1> NBG is only good for guild situations where there is a long term dedication of equipping ALL members. <br>
<br>
NBG is bullshit in pickup raids or groups because eventually the item WILL be sold.  Eventually your friend that won the eyepatch WILL sell it.  It's inevitable.  NBG vox/naggy raids turn into spy contests to see who sold their NBG loot first so that the players that didn't win shit can slander them and post nasty things about them on messageboards.<br>
<br>
Wake up and realize that NBG is completely ludicrous.  The loot isn't balanced, the winners will ALL sell eventually and that is fact. <br>
<br>
Take my real life example about a year  ago.  My enchanter at level 49 got an invite to a vox raid that was going to be NBG (the leaders of the raid were all melees).  Knowing that the RBB was the only good loot from vox I proceeded to log out my chanter and into my level 47 monk where I sent a tell and got into the raid on the condition that I knew how to skillfully pull ice giants.  <br>
<br>
We wiped to vox the first time due to lack of enchanters and clerics.  <br>
<br>
The 2nd time we pulled off a miracle with 1 cleric and 1 chanter.  RBB, white dragonscale, and the 100% weight reduce bag dropped along with a shitty spear.  The raid leaders said that NBG kicks in so monks and melees roll for RBB and bag.  <br>
<br>
This started and uproar of all casters who had been at this raid for 4 hours and were just now guaranteed that they wouldn't even have a CHANCE at winning a damn thing.  Despite the mess the roll commenced.  With only 8 or 9 melees present the roll did not have too bad of odds.  Well, I won the roll and almost crapped my pants.  One of the co-leaders started getting angry.  There was a long pause while I was waiting for the trade window.  The co-leader that did not have the item said that the other leader was his friend in RL and refused to give the RBB to me because I was a late invite (he had the 2nd highest roll).  After some harsh words back and forth he finally gave it up.  He did however, win the bag.<br>
<br>
For the next couple weeks when I would play my monk I would receive tells and inspections from people from the raid, obviously checking up on me.  They were just waiting for the opportunity to slander me.<br>
<br>
Well, I sold that RBB later on that 2nd week and my monk has served as a mule since then, but my chanter benefited greatly from the large amount of platinum I had received.<br>
<br>
This is the reason I posted on this thread, I have been there before and seen what NBG does to raids.  Instead of the players leaving the raid with the feeling of accomplishment and fairness of reward, they leave with animosity and regret.<br>
<br>
Kiradure, since you seem to be one of these raid leaders, can you enlighten me about the positive aspects of NBG after reading my experience?<br>
